# Dependency Rules Context

## Active Dependency Rules

- Runnable applications live in `./applications` and may import any required libraries from `./packages`.
- Libraries in `./packages` must not import from `./applications`.
- Keep layering: low-level “types/DTOs/domain abstractions” should be imported by higher-level/infrastructure libraries (e.g. `@aor/domain`, `@aor/common`), but not vice-versa.
- Treat `@aor/drizzle` as infrastructure: prefer importing it only from backend/batch adapter layers, not from UI/frontend code.

## Bounded Context Isolation

- Applications may import both read and write packages from multiple BCs.
- BC packages must not import packages from another BC directly.
- Cross-BC composition belongs to applications or explicit integration contracts.

## Integration Package Rule (`@aor/integration`)

- `@aor/integration` (`./packages/integration`) is the **only non-application package** allowed to import from multiple BCs.
- It may depend on `*-types` and `*-read` packages from any BC to implement cross-BC adapter logic.
- BC packages (`{bc}-types`, `{bc}-write`, `{bc}-read`) must **never** import from `@aor/integration`.
- Applications import `@aor/integration`; they do **not** re-implement cross-BC adapters already present in it.
- `@aor/integration` should not depend on `*-write` packages.

## Core Package Dependency Rules (`{bc}-core`)

When a BC defines a `core` package, the following additional rules apply:

- `{bc}-core` may only depend on `@aor/types` and `@aor/adapters`.
- `{bc}-write` and `{bc}-read` may depend on `{bc}-core`.
- `{bc}-types` re-exports public contracts from `{bc}-core` — consumers that already import from `{bc}-types` are not affected.
- Other BCs must not import `{bc}-core` directly; they must go through `{bc}-types`.
